  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both phrases\u2014**\"pick up someone at the airport\"** and **\"pick up someone from the airport\"**\u2014are grammatically correct. However, they can convey slightly different nuances depending on the context:\n\n1. **Pick up someone at the airport**\n   - **Usage:** Emphasizes the location where the picking up will occur.\n   - **Example:** \"I'll pick you up at the airport at 3 PM.\"\n\n2. **Pick up someone from the airport**\n   - **Usage:** Highlights the origin or source from which the person is being picked up.\n   - **Example:** \"Can you pick me up from the airport when I arrive?\"\n\n**Choosing Between \"at\" and \"from\":**\n- Use **\"at the airport\"** when you want to specify the exact location where the meeting or pickup will take place.\n- Use **\"from the airport\"** when emphasizing that the person is coming from the airport to another location.\n\n**In Summary:**\nBoth expressions are correct, and your choice between \"at\" and \"from\" should depend on the specific aspect you wish to emphasize in your sentence.",
